   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4ee79e11-b1cd-4187-b0f7-03035d1d2b17",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Document Linearization to Markdown or HTML with Textractor\n",
    "\n",
    "This example goes deeper on text linearization in Textractor. Text linearization is the conversion for a 2D document with words, lines, layouts and tables into a text string.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Installation\n",
    "\n",
    "To begin, install the `amazon-textract-textractor` package using pip.\n",
    "\n",
    "`pip install amazon-textract-textractor`\n",
    "\n",
    "There are various sets of dependencies available to tailor your installation to your use case. The base package will have sensible default, but you may want to install the PDF extra dependencies if your workflow uses PDFs with `pip install amazon-textract-textractor[pdf]`. You can read more on extra dependencies [in the documentation](https://aws-samples.github.io/amazon-textract-textractor/installation.html)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Calling Textract"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "44e7604d-6a1a-4493-b258-aa2f64ff2936",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "from PIL import Image\n",
    "from textractor import Textractor\n",
    "from textractor.visualizers.entitylist import EntityList\n",
    "from textractor.data.constants import TextractFeatures"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "dfa731a0-30c9-43ee-8bf6-b6dc90a7825d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/jpeg": "",
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGB size=706x914>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "image = Image.open(\"../../../tests/fixtures/paystub.jpg\").convert(\"RGB\")\n",
    "image"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f7318fb7-f61b-4e59-ae85-af3840b21c05",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can Textract's AnalyzeDocument API on this image. For the best possible extraction, we recommend using at least the `LAYOUT`, `TABLES` and `SIGNATURES` features to achieve the best possible reading order. OCR is always included with any AnalyzeDocument call. In this case we will also include `FORMS`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "3f30e75f-7507-4adf-88c4-56972140cee0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "extractor = Textractor(region_name=\"us-west-2\")\n",
    "\n",
    "document = extractor.analyze_document(\n",
    "    file_source=image,\n",
    "    features=[TextractFeatures.LAYOUT, TextractFeatures.TABLES, TextractFeatures.FORMS, TextractFeatures.SIGNATURES],\n",
    "    save_image=True\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f202dd86-9f05-4895-a666-a0498e1ab344",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Base linearization `.get_text()` is always available on all components of a document:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "e56d85c1-d08b-44e4-bc5d-0473880de729",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "CO.\tFILE\tDEPT.\tCLOCK\tNUMBER\n",
      "ABC\t126543\t123456\t12345\t00000000\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(document.tables[0].get_text())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "45078d3b-3139-4043-bb16-ec87a7196605",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However you can also use `.to_html()` and `.to_markdown()` to obtain the HTML and Markdown output respectively."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "2c41e05e-eb26-481c-b806-3bdb5eb61a57",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<table><tr><th>CO.</th><th>FILE</th><th>DEPT.</th><th>CLOCK</th><th>NUMBER</th></tr>\n",
      "<tr><td>ABC</td><td>126543</td><td>123456</td><td>12345</td><td>00000000</td></tr>\n",
      "</table>\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(document.tables[0].to_html())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "d8b57a61-547e-4eea-bd0e-1d4ba7bcf5a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "| CO.    |   FILE  |   DEPT.  |   CLOCK  |   NUMBER  |\n",
      "|--------|---------|----------|----------|-----------|\n",
      "| ABC    | 126543  |  123456  |   12345  | 00000000  |\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(document.tables[0].to_markdown())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "71835220-d626-4bb4-a3cc-0b0870e1c19e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Both the HTML and Markdown options will use the table cell types to identify headers automatically.\n",
    "\n",
    "You can apply your own configuration by building a `TextLinearizationConfig` object. Both `to_html()` and `.to_markdown()` are actually implemented as `TextLinearizationConfig` objects themselves. Say you wanted not to have header cells `<th>` in your table output, you could change the `HTMLLinearizationConfig` object and call `.get_text()` with it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "02238f14-e88f-4a94-b2ad-c9a37c2bd132",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<table><tr><td>CO.</td><td>FILE</td><td>DEPT.</td><td>CLOCK</td><td>NUMBER</td></tr>\n",
      "<tr><td>ABC</td><td>126543</td><td>123456</td><td>12345</td><td>00000000</td></tr>\n",
      "</table>\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from textractor.data.html_linearization_config import HTMLLinearizationConfig\n",
    "\n",
    "config = HTMLLinearizationConfig()\n",
    "config.table_cell_header_prefix = \"<td>\"\n",
    "config.table_cell_header_suffix = \"</td>\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(document.tables[0].get_text(config))"
   ]
  },
  {
